knowledge_graph.title: Babassu
knowledge_graph.description: Attalea speciosa, the babassu, babassu palm, babaçu, or cusi, is a palm native to the Amazon Rainforest region in South America. The babassu palm is the predominant species in the Maranhão Babaçu forests of Maranhão and Piauí states.

related_questions.question: What is babassu good for?
related_questions.snippet: Babassu oil has hydrating and anti-inflammatory properties, which soothe inflammation, hydrate the hair and skin, and promote skin healing. Lauric and myristic acids in babassu oil act as an effective emollient, which can be an excellent addition to hair and skin care formulations.

related_questions.question: Is babassu a palm oil?
related_questions.snippet: Babassu oil makes its way to you from the faraway forests of South America. It comes from a plant called the babassu palm tree, scientifically known as Attalea speciosa. This tree can be commonly found in the North of Brazil.

related_questions.question: Is babassu edible?
related_questions.snippet: Like the coconut palm, the babassu palm has many uses. The fruit may be used when green in the smoking of rubber. When ripe, it is eaten as a nutritious food.
